7.96,19.19,23.22,30.15,23.87,21.16,33.4,29.43,26.09,28.71,23.88,19.74,26.21,27.16,32.45,25.88,23.12,22.83,21.67,19.81,20.53,18.49,22.61,17.07,20.09,19.14,13.88,14.18,13.86,16.46,13.82,16.9,19.32,14.91,12.8,12.48,13.35,13.26,14.01,14.44,12.78,18.0,13.0,14.28,12.3,12.51,16.6,14.65,22.38,16.96,19.11,15.2,14.1,27.62,18.07,15.84,15.27,24.23,21.77,28.45,18.22,17.69,19.83,17.2,20.38,14.22,14.71,16.63,18.6,17.51,16.59,14.0,16.75,18.64,19.55,22.37,25.78,17.83,17.82,18.92,18.41,16.73]}},"releases":{"fomc":"Jul 29","ecb":"Jul 23","jobs":"Aug 7","ismMfg":"Aug 3","ismServices":"Aug 5","claims":"Weekly (Thu)","cpi":"Aug 12 (est.)","ppi":"Aug 13 (est.)","retail":"Aug 17 (est.)","housing":"Aug 17 (est.)","existing":"Jul 21 (est.)","pce":"Jul 28 (est.)","gdp":"Jul 28 (est.)","umich":"Aug 14 (est.)","chinaPMI":"Jul 31 (est.)","daily":"Daily","gdpnowKey":"Updates ~weekly"},"commentary":{"source":"claude","generated":"2026-07-18","items":[{"tag":"Energy","text":"WTI edged up to $79.20 (+$0.26 w/w) and Brent surged to $81.62 (+$5.93 w/w) as Middle East supply-risk premium rebuilds. The Brent-WTI spread widening to ~$2.40 signals tightening seaborne supply, a direct cost-push input for energy-intensive credits and leveraged issuers with unhedged commodity exposure. For distressed/special-sits credit, monitor E&P and midstream obligors with floating-rate debt \u2014 higher realized oil may relieve covenant pressure for some, but broader input-cost pass-through keeps margins under stress across industrials."},{"tag":"Labor","text":"June payrolls printed a deeply disappointing +57K (vs. +129K prior), yet unemployment ticked down to 4.2% and claims fell to 208K, suggesting the labor market is bifurcating rather than collapsing \u2014 layoffs remain low but gross hiring has stalled. AHE accelerated to +3.52% YoY, reinforcing services-sector wage stickiness that complicates the Fed's disinflation path. For credit investors, the weak payroll print raises refinancing risk for consumer-facing, labor-cost-intensive issuers if demand softens, while tight claims data provides a near-term floor for default rates."},{"tag":"Inflation","text":"Headline CPI eased sharply to 3.46% (from 4.17%) and core CPI fell to 2.57% \u2014 the most encouraging disinflation print of 2026 \u2014 but PCE headline reaccelerated to 4.07% and PPI remains elevated at 5.51%, pointing to sticky pipeline pressures. The CPI/PCE divergence is critical: the Fed targets PCE, so the more favorable CPI read does not translate directly into policy relief. For credit, the spread between softening consumer prices and still-hot producer prices is squeezing margins on leveraged mid-market issuers, particularly in manufacturing and retail supply chains."},{"tag":"Policy & Rates","text":"The 10Y UST jumped to 4.57% (+17bps w/w) and the 2Y to 4.16% (+7bps), steepening the curve to +41bps \u2014 the most since the normalization cycle began \u2014 as the market reprices Fed cuts further out given stubborn PCE. The Fed funds rate holds at 3.75%, meaning the real rate front-end is materially positive and restrictive. For special situations credit, the rate backup increases pressure on issuers with near-term maturities: floating-rate term loans reprice instantly while fixed-rate bonds face duration extension in any refinancing, widening the 'maturity trap' for overleveraged capital structures."},{"tag":"Credit Markets","text":"HY OAS compressed marginally to 271bps (-1bp) while IG OAS widened slightly to 78bps (+3bps), suggesting modest risk-on at the high-yield end despite rate turbulence \u2014 VIX declined to 16.73 from 18.41, corroborating the complacency in credit spreads. At 271bps HY OAS, the market is not pricing meaningful default risk, which creates asymmetric risk for special situations investors: entry-level distressed plays require a catalyst to gap wider. The IG widening to 78bps, while small, may reflect early repricing of interest-coverage deterioration as floating-rate IG borrowers feel the full weight of 3.75% base rates."},{"tag":"Growth","text":"GDPNow tracking has improved to 1.68% for Q2 (from 1.24%) but remains well below the prior Q1 GDP print of 2.1%, and the broader trend of deceleration is confirmed by the payrolls miss, weak UMich sentiment (44.8), and a savings rate stuck at 3.0%. ISM Services at 54.0 \u2014 solid but easing from 54.5 \u2014 is the key counterweight: the services engine is still running, implying recession is not imminent, but the economy is operating in the slow-growth corridor where credit stress is most likely to surface in leveraged capital structures with thin coverage ratios. Special-sits investors should focus on issuers where EBITDA growth assumptions embedded in 2024-vintage underwriting are now clearly unachievable at current run-rates."},{"tag":"Consumer & Housing","text":"Retail sales rose just +0.2% m/m in June (control group +0.5%), weighed down by a 5.3% drop at gas stations as pump prices fell \u2014 the underlying consumer is resilient but not accelerating. Existing home sales slipped to 4.09M SAAR from 4.19M, while housing starts surged to 1,427K from 1,199K, suggesting builders are getting ahead of demand even as the 30Y mortgage rate climbed to 6.55%. For credit, the divergence between rising starts and falling resales signals near-term oversupply risk in regional housing markets, pressuring homebuilder and CMBS-adjacent credits, while the consumer spending floor limits downside for retail REIT and ABS collateral."}]},"extraSeries":{"ecb":{"value":"2.25%","delta":"Hiked 25bps at June 17 meeting (first increase since 2023); hold expected at July 23 meeting (~93% probability)","dir":"up"},"chinaPMI":{"value":"50.3","delta":"Up from 50.0 in May; beat consensus of 50.1; driven by AI/tech export demand and tariff front-loading ahead of Section 301 levies","dir":"up"},"ismServices":{"value":"54.0","delta":"Down 0.5pts from 54.5 in May; 24th consecutive month in expansion; employment sub-index turned positive for first time in 4 months","dir":"down"},"retailSales":{"value":"+0.2% m/m","delta":"Slowed sharply from +1.0% in May; below +0.3% consensus; gas station drag of -5.3%; control group +0.5% was solid","dir":"down"},"existingHome":{"value":"4.09M","delta":"Down from 4.19M prior month; 30Y mortgage at 6.55% continues to suppress turnover and lock-in effect persists","dir":"down"}},"themes":{"refiWall":"The 2026-27 HY/leveraged loan refinancing wall remains a central risk as the 10Y backed up to 4.57% and base rates hold at 3.75%, keeping all-in borrowing costs elevated; issuers that need to term out 2027 maturities into this rate environment face materially higher interest burdens, and the combination of decelerating EBITDA growth with sticky financing costs is compressing coverage ratios \u2014 watch for covenant-lite structures where the first signal of stress will be a missed refinancing rather than a covenant breach.","tariffs":"Section 301 tariffs on Chinese goods are set to take effect at end-July, and China's June manufacturing PMI reflected meaningful front-loading by US importers seeking to build inventory ahead of the levy; FT reporting suggests the US is pushing for a 15-20% minimum tariff on EU goods as well, broadening the trade-restriction perimeter \u2014 for credit, the downstream effect is margin compression for import-dependent US issuers and working capital inflation that strains revolving credit facilities heading into H2.","mideast":"The Iran conflict and related Strait of Hormuz disruptions remain the dominant tail risk for energy prices and global supply chains, having directly catalyzed the ECB's first rate hike since 2023 and kept ISM Services prices elevated at 67.7; the ISM commentary flagged that petroleum-related cost pressures should ease in fall 2026 assuming Hormuz shipping lanes continue to normalize, but any re-escalation would rapidly reprice Brent back toward $90+ and reignite the stagflationary impulse that currently keeps both the Fed and ECB in restrictive postures."}}